KZN Christian Council Cardinal Wilfrid Napier said the coronavirus would not stop them from practicing their religion their faith but they would implement some changes. DURBAN - KwaZulu-Natal religious leaders said they would change some of their practices to stop the transmission of coronavirus (COVID-19) to congregants. Chairperson of the KwaZulu-Natal Christian Council Cardinal Wilfrid Napier said church services, Easter celebrations, weddings and funerals will not go ahead as usual considering the increasing number of new infections in the country. However, Napier said they remain hopeful that the world would be able to defeat the virus.  The cardinal said the coronavirus would not stop them from practicing their religion and expressing their faith but they would implement some changes. “We will try to implement what they call social distancing.” Meanwhile, President Cyril Ramaphosa has pleaded with religious leaders to help contain the spread of COVID-19. Ramaphosa said measures that he had put in place - after declaring the national state of disaster - were in the interests of all South Africans. Napier said they would adhere to all precautionary measures stipulated by the government. To track the latest developments around the coronavirus both in South Africa and abroad, click on this live status report from Strategix.